s. Should a judge feel confident in defining common words in the texts without the aid of a linguist? How is the meaning communicated by the text determined? Should the communicative meaning of texts be decisive, or at least influential? To fully engage and probe these questions of interpretation, this volume draws upon a variety of experts from several fields, who collectively examine the interpretation of legal texts. In The Nature of Legal Interpretation, the contributors argue that the meaning of language is crucial to the interpretation of legal texts, such as statutes, constitutions, and contracts. Accordingly, expert analysis of language from linguists, philosophers, and legal scholars should influence how courts interpret legal texts. Offering insightful new interdisciplinary perspectives on originalism and legal interpretation, these essays put forth a significant and provocative discussion of how best to characterize the nature of language in legal texts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aLawxInterpretation and construction. 0aLawxLanguagexPhilosophy. 0aLawxLanguage. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  aGadamer.  aconstitutional interpretation.  adeferentialism.  alaw and language.  alegal interpretation.  alinguistics.  aphilosophy of language.  apragmatics.  asemantics.  astatutory interpretation.1 aAllott, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenawalt, Kent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMootz, Francis J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPetroski, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRavitch, Frank S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosen, Gideon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/